## Rules

{% if profile.error_handling.error_strategy == 'exceptions' %}
1. Use custom error classes instead of generic `Error` or `Exception`
2. Always include meaningful error messages with context
3. Catch specific exceptions — never catch-all without re-throwing
4. Log errors before re-throwing or returning error responses
{% elif profile.error_handling.error_strategy == 'result-types' %}
1. Use Result/Either types for expected failures
2. Reserve exceptions for truly exceptional circumstances
3. Always handle both success and error paths
4. Propagate errors with context — don't swallow them
{% else %}
1. Follow the project's existing error handling patterns
2. Always include meaningful error messages
3. Log errors with appropriate severity levels
{% endif %}

{% if profile.error_handling.custom_error_classes %}
## Custom Error Classes

Use these existing error classes — do not create duplicates:

{% for cls in profile.error_handling.custom_error_classes %}
- `{{ cls }}`
{% endfor %}

> Extend these classes for new error types. Do not use generic `Error` or `Exception`.
{% endif %}

{% if profile.error_handling.logging_framework or profile.error_handling.logging_frameworks %}
## Logging

- Use `{{ profile.error_handling.logging_framework or profile.error_handling.logging_frameworks | first }}` — do not introduce alternative loggers
{% if profile.error_handling.logging_config_file %}
- Config: `{{ profile.error_handling.logging_config_file }}`
{% endif %}
- Use appropriate log levels: DEBUG for development, INFO for operations, WARN for recoverable issues, ERROR for failures
{% if profile.error_handling.structured_logging %}
- This project uses **structured logging** — include key-value context in log entries (request IDs, user IDs, etc.)
{% else %}
- Include structured context in log entries (request IDs, user IDs, etc.)
{% endif %}
- Never log sensitive data (passwords, tokens, PII)
{% endif %}

